 type\n   690→Magnetic\n   691→Screw length\n   692→Up to 50 mm (35 mm thread length)\n   693→Head type\n   694→Counter sunk\n   695→하드웨어 사양\n   696→79\n   697→\n   698→=== PAGE 80 ===\n   699→Supported Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium 2/2\n   700→Appearance\n   701→Standard\n   702→DIN 7500 M\n   703→DIN 14586 C\n   704→DIN 7982 C\n   705→Thread size and Bit holder/ Bit extender\n   706→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n   707→20 / M2 / K20\n   708→N/A\n   709→N/A\n   710→ST2.2 / 2.2 / KB22 / K22\n   711→N/A\n   712→2.5 / M2.5 / KB25 / K25\n   713→N/A\n   714→N/A\n   715→ST 2.9\n   716→N/A\n   717→3 / M3 / KB30 / K30\n   718→N/A\n   719→N/A\n   720→ST3.5.3 / 3.5 / KB35 / K35\n   721→N/A\n   722→ST 3.9\n   723→N/A\n   724→4 / M4 / KB40 / K40\n   725→N/A\n   726→N/A\n   727→ST 4.2\n   728→N/A\n   729→ST 4.8\n   730→N/A\n   731→50 / M5 / KB50 / K50\n   732→N/A\n   733→N/A\n   734→ST 5.5\n   735→N/A\n   736→60 / M6\n   737→N/A\n   738→N/A\n   739→ST 6.3\n   740→N/A\n   741→Supported Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   742→Material type\n   743→Magnetic\n   744→Screw length\n   745→Up to 50 mm (35 mm thread length)\n   746→Head type\n   747→Counter sunk\n   748→Flat round with flange\n   749→하드웨어 사양\n   750→80\n   751→\n   752→=== PAGE 81 ===\n   753→Supported Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   754→Appearance\n   755→Standard\n   756→ISO 4042\n   757→WN 1411\n   758→WN 5451\n   759→Thread size and Bit holder/ Bit extender\n   760→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n   761→20 / M2 / K20\n   762→N/A\n   763→N/A\n   764→ST2.2 / 2.2 / KB22 / K22\n   765→N/A\n   766→2.5 / M2.5 / KB25 / K25\n   767→3 / M3 / KB30 / K30\n   768→ST3.5.3 / 3.5 / KB35 / K35\n   769→N/A\n   770→4 / M4 / KB40 / K40\n   771→50 / M5 / KB50 / K50\n   772→N/A\n   773→60 / M6\n   774→N/A\n   775→N/A\n   776→Guidance on Achievable Depth for Self-tapping Screws\n   777→How deep a screw can be self-tapped highly depends on the screw material and the\n   778→workpiece material. There are three examples below of what the maximum depth is for a\n   779→specific screw to go into a specific material.\n   780→Example of WN 1411 in POM\n   781→Screw Size\n   782→Depth\n   783→K18x10\n   784→10\n   785→K20x10\n   786→10\n   787→K22x16\n   788→16\n   789→K25x16\n   790→16\n   791→K30x20\n   792→20\n   793→K35x30\n   794→30\n   795→하드웨어 사양\n   796→81\n   797→\n   798→=== PAGE 82 ===\n   799→Screw Size\n   800→Depth\n   801→K40x30\n   802→30\n   803→K50x30\n   804→30\n   805→Example of WN 1411 in NYLON PA Type 6\n   806→Screw Size\n   807→Depth\n   808→K18x10\n   809→10\n   810→K20x10\n   811→10\n   812→K22x16\n   813→16\n   814→K25x16\n   815→16\n   816→K30x20\n   817→20\n   818→K35x30\n   819→30\n   820→K40x30\n   821→30\n   822→K50x30\n   823→30\n   824→Example of DIN 7500 M in Aluminium EN AW-5754\n   825→Screw Size\n   826→Depth\n   827→M2x12\n   828→12\n   829→M2.5x20\n   830→20\n   831→M3x30\n   832→25\n   833→M4x30\n   834→30\n   835→M5x30\n   836→30\n   837→M6x30\n   838→11\n   839→There are three potential outcomes when testing a self-tapping screw:\n   840→1. The screw goes all the way in and is tightened with the set target torque. This is\n   841→successful operation.\n   842→2. The screw breaks while screwing in and the Screwdriver returns a result code / runtime\n   843→error: 10 - “Torque dropped unexpectedly”. This means that the screw cannot handle\n   844→such high torque on a material that hard.\n   845→하드웨어 사양\n   846→82\n   847→\n   848→=== PAGE 83 ===\n   849→3. The Screwdriver stops halfway through and returns a result code / runtime error: 4 -\n   850→“Torque exceeded prematurely”. This means that a higher torque is needed to go through\n   851→that material with that screw. A solution could be to set a higher tightening torque.\n   852→For a successful tapping, ensure that the hole is made according to the screw manufacturer\n   853→specifications.\n   854→Torque accuracy Metric\n   855→Torque accuracy US Standard\n   856→하드웨어 사양\n   857→83\n   858→\n   859→=== PAGE 84 ===\n   860→Screw-bit System\n   861→This system will highly increase the efficacy of the screws to be picked up, aligned with the\n   862→bit, moved around with the Screwdriver and screwed in/out. Therefore, it is highly\n   863→recommended to set up the Screw-bit System correctly to keep a high success rate.\n   864→Example of the Screw-bit System for an ISO 14579, M2 screw.\n   865→1 - Screw\n   866→2 - Screw fix\n   867→3 - Screw carrier\n   868→4 - Bit\n   869→5 - Bit holder\n   870→The following sections explain the different components of the Screw-bit System and how to\n   871→set it up correctly.\n   872→Screws\n   873→The first step is to know what type of screw is going to be used. The screw type will define\n   874→what type of screw fix (in any), screw carrier, bit, and bit holder shall be used.\n   875→참고\n   876→Use a chamfer for better reliability when making the screw hole.\n   877→The recommended screw types for the Screwdriver are the ones that have the properties\n   878→mentioned previously in the Supported Screws tables.\n   879→Screw Fix and Screw Carrier\n   880→Select the right screw fix and screw carrier depending on the screw type and the size to\n   881→maximize the efficacy of the Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n   882→하드웨어 사양\n   883→84\n   884→\n   885→=== PAGE 85 ===\n   886→•\n   887→Metric Screws\n   888→•\n   889→US Standard Screws\n   890→•\n   891→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n   892→•\n   893→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   894→The screw fixes are needed for the DIN 912, ISO 4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580, DIN 7981C /\n   895→ISO 7049, DIN 7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 1411, WN 5451 and ASME B18.3 HEX\n   896→Cylinder screw types. The screw fixes have signifiers to show what size of screw they\n   897→support.\n   898→Screw fixes for Metric - DIN 912, ISO 4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580, DIN 7981C / ISO 7049,\n   899→DIN 7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 1411, WN 5451\n   900→M1.6\n   901→M2\n   902→M2.5\n   903→M3\n   904→M4\n   905→M5\n   906→M6\n   907→Screw fixes for US Standard - ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder, DIN 7981C / ISO 7049, DIN\n   908→7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 5451\n   909→1#\n   910→2#\n   911→4#\n   912→6#\n   913→8#\n   914→10#\n   915→1/4\"\n   916→The screw carriers also have signifiers to help identifying what screw type and size they can\n   917→be used with.\n   918→Screw thread size\n   919→Screw type illustration\n   920→Bits\n   921→Select the right bit depending on the screw type and size to maximize the efficacy of the\n   922→Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n   923→•\n   924→Metric Screws\n   925→•\n   926→US Standard Screws\n   927→•\n   928→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n   929→•\n   930→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   931→하드웨어 사양\n   932→85\n   933→\n   934→=== PAGE 86 ===\n   935→The bits have signifiers to help identifying what bit type and size they are.\n   936→Screw type standard\n   937→Shows bit size and type\n   938→Din 912 / ISO 4762\n   939→ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder\n   940→ISO 14579\n   941→ISO 14580\n   942→ISO 14581\n   943→DIN 7500 M\n   944→DIN 14586 C\n   945→WN 5251\n   946→ISO 4042\n   947→WN 5451\n   948→ASME B18.6.3 Torx Button head\n   949→ASME B18.6.3 Torx Counter sunk\n   950→DIN 7985A\n   951→DIN 7981C / ISO 7049\n   952→DIN 7981F / ISO 7049\n   953→DIN 7982 C\n   954→DIN 7983 C\n   955→WN 1411\n   956→ASME B18.6.3 Cross recessed Button head\n   957→Supported bit shank properties:\n   958→•\n   959→Type 1/4\" HEX\n   960→•\n   961→Length 25 mm\n   962→참고\n   963→Bits longer than 25 mm could be used. However, the screw carrier and the\n   964→screw fix might not hold the screw properly in place.\n   965→Bit Holder\n   966→Select the right bit holder depending on the screw type and size to maximize the efficacy of\n   967→the Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n   968→•\n   969→Metric Screws\n   970→•\n   971→US Standard Screws\n   972→•\n   973→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n   974→•\n   975→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   976→The bit holder generates a magnetic force that will keep the screw attached and aligned to\n   977→the bit.\n   978→There are two types of bit holders:\n   979→하드웨어 사양\n   980→86\n   981→\n   982→=== PAGE 87 ===\n   983→•\n   984→Bit Holder A: Generates a higher magnetic force. It is commonly used for the bigger and\n   985→heavier screws.\n   986→•\n   987→Bit Holder B: Generates a lower magnetic force. It is commonly used for the smaller and\n   988→lighter screws.\n   989→경고\n   990→If Bit Holder A is used for smaller and lighter screws instead of Bit Holder B,\n   991→the screws can jump from the Screw Feeder to the Screwdriver because of\n   992→the higher magnetic force.\n   993→Bit Extenders 50 and 100 mm\n   994→The bit extenders are a long version of the previously described bit holders. Bit extenders\n   995→are useful to reach narrow spaces.\n   996→The bit extenders have a lock nut to tighten against the screw carrier to ensure that the\n   997→screw carrier does not move out of position over time.\n   998→When the bit extenders are mounted on the Screwdriver, the maximum total radial runout\n   999→can be up to 0.5 mm (measured below the thread as shown in the following picture).\n  1000→The bit extenders need to be purchased separately by contacting your vendor where the\n  1001→Screwdriver was purchased.\n  1002→•\n  1003→Bit extender type A 50 mm - PN 109301\n  1004→•\n  1005→Bit extender type B 50 mm - PN 109289\n  1006→•\n  1007→Bit extender type A 100 mm - PN 109290\n  1008→•\n  1009→Bit extender type B 100 mm - PN 109298\n  1010→For more information on the mechanical dimensions, go to the 7.2.2.1. Mechanical\n  1011→Drawings section.\n  1012→하드웨어 사양\n  1013→87\n  1014→\n  1015→=== PAGE 88 ===\n  1016→Set up the Screw-bit System\n  1017→1. Place the bit into the bit holder.\n  1018→2. Place the screw carrier on the bit holder.\n  1019→3. All screw carriers must be adjusted so that the screw head sits stable on the screw\n  1020→carrier avoiding a gap in between. This needs to be done to ensure high performance of\n  1021→the Screw-bit System.\n  1022→See the pictures below as reference.\n  1023→Appearance\n  1024→Adjustment method\n  1025→하드웨어 사양\n  1026→88\n  1027→\n  1028→=== PAGE 89 ===\n  1029→Appearance\n  1030→Adjustment method\n  1031→Din 912 / ISO\n  1032→4762 /\n  1033→ISO 14579 /\n  1034→ISO 14580 /\n  1035→ASME B18.3\n  1036→Hex Cylinder\n  1037→ISO 14581 /\n  1038→ASME\n  1039→B18.6 HEX\n  1040→Counter\n  1041→sunk /\n  1042→ASME\n  1043→B18.6.3\n  1044→Torx\n  1045→Counter\n  1046→sunk\n  1047→DIN 7985A /\n  1048→ASME B18.6.3\n  1049→Cross\n  1050→recessed\n  1051→Button head /\n  1052→ASME B18.6.3\n  1053→Torx Button\n  1054→head\n  1055→4. When this is achieved, remove the screw and push in the screw fix (only Din 912, ISO\n  1056→4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580 and ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder screw types).\n  1057→The final setup of the Screw-bit System with the screw in place should look like in the\n  1058→pictures below.\n  1059→하드웨어 사양\n  1060→89\n  1061→\n  1062→=== PAGE 90 ===\n  1063→Screw\n  1064→standard\n  1065→Din 912 /\n  1066→ISO 4762 /\n  1067→ISO 14579 /\n  1068→ISO 14580 /\n  1069→ASME\n  1070→B18.3 Hex\n  1071→Cylinder\n  1072→ISO\n  1073→14581 /\n  1074→ASME\n  1075→B18.6 HEX\n  1076→Counter\n  1077→sunk /\n  1078→ASME\n  1079→B18.6.3\n  1080→Torx\n  1081→Counter\n  1082→sunk\n  1083→DIN 7985A /\n  1084→ASME\n  1085→B18.6.3\n  1086→Cross\n  1087→recessed\n  1088→Button\n  1089→head /\n  1090→ASME\n  1091→B18.6.3 Torx\n  1092→Button head\n  1093→Screw-bit\n  1094→System\n  1095→appearance\n  1096→Attaching the Screw-bit System to the Screwdriver\n  1097→To attach the Screw-bit System to the Screwdriver, follow the instructions below.\n  1098→1. Move the shank to the highest possible\n  1099→value by using the user interface in the\n  1100→robot or in the Web Client.\n  1101→2. Detach the Screwdriver from the Quick\n  1102→Changer.\n  1103→하드웨어 사양\n  1104→90\n  1105→\n  1106→=== PAGE 91 ===\n  1107→3. Remove the lid.\n  1108→4. Place the hex shape of the bit holder\n  1109→inside of the end of the Screwdriver's\n  1110→shank. The system will be attached to the\n  1111→Screwdriver by a magnetic force.\n  1112→5. Ensure that the bit holder is perfectly\n  1113→attached by gently shaking it to make sure\n  1114→it is not loose.\n  1115→Detaching the Screw-bit System from the Screwdriver\n  1116→To remove the Screw-bit System from the Screwdriver's shank, follow the instructions below.\n  1117→1. Move the shank all the way out to the\n  1118→highest possible value by operating the\n  1119→user interface in the robot or in the Web\n  1120→Client.\n  1121→2. Use the provided key to grab the bit\n  1122→holder. While holding the key, move the\n  1123→shank inwards (to a lower value) by\n  1124→operating the user interface in the robot or\n  1125→in the Web Client.\n  1126→Overview of the Items Needed Depending on the Screw Type and Size\n  1127→In the following tables, an overview is shown of the items needed depending on the screw\n  1128→type and size. Based on what screw type and size you have, search for the screw standard\n  1129→and the thread size and find what kind of bit, screw fix, screw carrier and bit holder you will\n  1130→need.\n  1131→하드웨어 사양\n  1132→91\n  1133→\n  1134→=== PAGE 92 ===\n  1135→For more information, see the example.\n  1136→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1137→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1138→Head type\n  1139→Cylinder\n  1140→Counter sunk\n  1141→Button head\n  1142→Screw\n  1143→standard\n  1144→Thread Size\n  1145→Bit holder, bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1146→M1.6\n  1147→N/A\n  1148→N/A\n  1149→N/A\n  1150→N/A\n  1151→M2\n  1152→N/A\n  1153→하드웨어 사양\n  1154→92\n  1155→\n  1156→=== PAGE 93 ===\n  1157→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1158→M2.5\n  1159→N/A\n  1160→M3\n  1161→M4\n  1162→M5\n  1163→M6\n  1164→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1165→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1166→Head type\n  1167→Cylinder\n  1168→Button head\n  1169→Counter sunk\n  1170→Screw\n  1171→standard\n  1172→HEX\n  1173→Cross recessed Torx\n  1174→HEX\n  1175→Torx\n  1176→Thread Size Bit holder, bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1177→하드웨어 사양\n  1178→93\n  1179→\n  1180→=== PAGE 94 ===\n  1181→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1182→1# \n  1183→N/A\n  1184→N/A\n  1185→N/A\n  1186→N/A\n  1187→2# \n  1188→N/A\n  1189→4# \n  1190→6# \n  1191→8# \n  1192→10#\n  1193→하드웨어 사양\n  1194→94\n  1195→\n  1196→=== PAGE 95 ===\n  1197→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1198→12#\n  1199→N/A\n  1200→N/A\n  1201→N/A\n  1202→1/4\"\n  1203→N/A\n  1204→N/A\n  1205→N/A\n  1206→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1207→Aluminium\n  1208→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1209→Aluminium 1/2\n  1210→Head type\n  1211→Pan head\n  1212→Flat round with\n  1213→flange\n  1214→Lens head\n  1215→Appearance\n  1216→Standard\n  1217→DIN 7981 C/ ISO\n  1218→7049\n  1219→DIN 7981 F/ ISO\n  1220→7049\n  1221→WN 5251\n  1222→DIN 7983 C\n  1223→Thread Size\n  1224→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1225→ST2.2 / 2.2 /\n  1226→KB22 / K22\n  1227→N/A\n  1228→하드웨어 사양\n  1229→95\n  1230→\n  1231→"}]},"uuid":"bf185ffb-9906-499a-a976-403e6548ee8d","timestamp":"2026-02-26T01:32:12.968Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d90292b6-3dd2-4950-8a5b-15ae6ec1943c"}
